{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499249","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499249"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T09:57:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T09:57:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1473"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1473"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.06,0.74,0.09,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1473"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42334"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1473"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1473"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27357"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"306"},{"type":"tags","id":"1132"},{"type":"tags","id":"1397"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5339"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5443"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42334","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/42334"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to his General practitioner with left foot pain that has worsened over the past two months. The pain is localized to the left heel and is exacerbated upon walking. He has a medical history of diabetes mellitus which is poorly controlled. His medications include metformin and sitagliptin. On examination the heel appears swollen, hot and erythematous. On palpation the heel is markedly tender. A radiograph of the left foot is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Plantar fasciitis","Achilles tendinitis","Osteomyelitis","Apophysitis","Gout"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Eosteomyelitis\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient has diabetes mellitus which is a risk factor of osteomyelitis. Physical examination findings also support the diagnosis as the heel appears swollen and hot. Moreover the radiographic finding show calcaneal osteomyelitis with a lucent lesion,\u00a0completely separated from the surrounding bone (also call sequestrum).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlantar fasciitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign, often self-limiting condition that occurs when the plantar fascia insertion on the calcaneum becomes inflamed. Most cases of plantar fasciitis resolve with time. NSAIDs, and physiotherapy can help with resolution of symptoms. This is not the correct answer as patient is showing signs of infection with a swollen, hot and erythematous heel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAchilles tendinitis \u003C/strong\u003Eis another condition that can present with heel pain. Pain maybe due to pathology of the tendon or retrocaclaneal bursa. Radiographs may show a deformity of the tendon or an insertional spur. Physiotherapy and analgesics can help. The clinical scenario and imaging in this case does not support a diagnosis of achilles tendinitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECalcaneal \u003Cstrong\u003Eapophysitis\u003C/strong\u003E or Sever disease is common in the paediatric age group especially in boys. It is associated with sports related activity. Imaging is not required for diagnosis. Treatment options include physiotherapy and analgesics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGout\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents in the form of severe attacks of pain in a single or multiple joints. The heel can be a site of involvement in gout but the most common site of involvement is the first MTP. The patient is usually well in between attacks. In the current scenario, the history is suggestive of a continuous disease course rather than episodic attacks.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Chronic or untreated cases of osteomyelitis can manifest as sequestrum formation on imaging."],"references":["Chen K, Balloch R. Management of calcaneal osteomyelitis. Clin Podiatr Med Surg. 2010 Jul;27(3):417-29. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20691374/","Imboden JB, Hellmann DB, Stone JA. Current diagnosis \u0026 treatment in rheumatology (4ed). McGraw Hill Professional; 2020."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27357"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1473"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14161"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14161","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14161"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e3a74391-8c65-4b8b-b613-f53253381e4f.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e3a74391-8c65-4b8b-b613-f53253381e4f.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":545}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27357","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/27357"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-02-07T15:59:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-02-07T15:59:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1473"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42334"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"